To implement gravity and add a platform to the simple platformer game in React, we can add some more state to our `GameMain` component to manage the player's velocity and whether or not they're currently grounded. Here's an update to our previous implementation that includes gravity and a simple platform:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from "react";

// Constants for gravity and jumping
const GRAVITY = 0.5;
const JUMP_STRENGTH = -10; // Negative because the Y axis is downward

const Platform = ({ width, height, top, left }) => {
  const style = {
    position: "absolute",
    width: `${width}px`,
    height: `${height}px`,
    backgroundColor: "brown",
    left: `${left}px`,
    top: `${top}px`,
  };

  return <div style={style} />;
};

const Player = ({ position }) => {
  const style = {
    position: "absolute",
    width: "50px",
    height: "50px",
    backgroundColor: "blue",
    left: `${position.x}px`,
    top: `${position.y}px`,
  };

  return <div style={style} />;
};

function GameMain() {
  const [playerPosition, setPlayerPosition] = useState({ x: 100, y: 100 });
  const [playerVelocity, setPlayerVelocity] = useState({ x: 0, y: 0 });
  const [isGrounded, setIsGrounded] = useState(false);
  const requestRef = useRef();
  const lastTimeRef = useRef(0);

  // Platform
  const platform = {
    width: 400,
    height: 20,
    top: 500,
    left: 200,
  };

  const updateGame = (time) => {
    const deltaTime = time - lastTimeRef.current;
    lastTimeRef.current = time;

    // Update physics
    let newVelocity = {
      x: playerVelocity.x,
      y: playerVelocity.y + GRAVITY,
    };

    let newPosition = {
      x: playerPosition.x + newVelocity.x * deltaTime,
      y: Math.min(platform.top, playerPosition.y + newVelocity.y * deltaTime),
    };

    // Check if player is on the platform
    if (newPosition.y === platform.top) {
      setIsGrounded(true);
      newVelocity.y = 0;
    } else {
      setIsGrounded(false);
    }

    // Update state with the new position and velocity
    setPlayerPosition(newPosition);
    setPlayerVelocity(newVelocity);

    if (!isGrounded && newPosition.y >= platform.top - 50 && 
        playerPosition.x >= platform.left - 50 && playerPosition.x <= platform.left + platform.width) {
      setPlayerPosition((prev) => ({ ...prev, y: platform.top - 50 }));
      setPlayerVelocity((prev) => ({ ...prev, y: 0 }));
      setIsGrounded(true);
    }

    requestRef.current = requestAnimationFrame(updateGame);
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    const handleKeyPress = (event) => {
      if (event.key === "ArrowRight") {
        setPlayerPosition((prev) => ({ ...prev, x: prev.x + 5 }));
      } else if (event.key === "ArrowLeft") {
        setPlayerPosition((prev) => ({ ...prev, x: prev.x - 5 }));
      } else if (event.key === "ArrowUp" && isGrounded) {
        setPlayerVelocity((prev) => ({ ...prev, y: JUMP_STRENGTH }));
        setIsGrounded(false);
      }
    };

    window.addEventListener("keydown", handleKeyPress);

    return () => {
      window.removeEventListener("keydown", handleKeyPress);
    };
  }, [isGrounded]);

  useEffect(() => {
    requestRef.current = requestAnimationFrame(updateGame);
    return () => cancelAnimationFrame(requestRef.current);
  }, []); // This will start your game loop

  return (
    <div style={{ position: 'relative', width: '800px', height: '600px', background: 'lightgreen' }}>
      <Player position={playerPosition} />
      <Platform {...platform} />
    </div>
  );
}

export default GameMain;
```

Here's what's happening in this code:

1. There is now a `Platform` component that simply renders a rectangular div at a specified position.
2. Gravity is applied to the player's `y` velocity each frame, pulling the player downwards.
3. When the up arrow key is pressed and the player is grounded, a negative y-velocity is applied to simulate a jump.
4. When the player lands on the platform, their y-velocity is set to zero, and they are marked as grounded.

This is still quite a rudimentary system, and in a more complex game, you would want to handle collision detection more robustly, possibly by implementing an AABB (Axis-Aligned Bounding Box) collision system or using a physics engine. You also might want to factor in delta time (`deltaTime`) for consistent motion regardless of framerate, but that is omitted here for simplicity.

